<TITLE> BNP protests Amar Desh closure </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 2 (bdnews24.com)  Main opposition BNP announced on Wednesday afternoon programmes across the country in protest at the closure of the Bengali daily 'Amar Desh' and the arrest of its acting editor Mahmudur Rahman. Mahmudur Rahman, the acting editor of pro-opposition BNP daily 'Amar Desh was arrested on Wednesday morning after the newspaper was closed on Tuesday night. BNP secretary general Khandker Delwar Hossain made the announcement at a press briefing at the party's central office in Naya Paltan in the city. He also demanded that the newspaper should be allowed to reopen, and that Mahmudur Rahman should be released unconditionally. He alleged that the government was being vindictive against the paper as the was publishing reports of its corruption, misrule and failures. "The government wants to keep running 'controlled newspapers' in the country through its repressive policy." he went on. "The government is trying to design a blue-print to bring all newspapers under its control." He termed the government's behaviour as 'undemocratic' and 'motivated' and said, "This government does not believe in the freedom of press. In the past, they also closed newspapers other than four." He also criticised the process by which Mahmudur Rahman was arrested. BNP's senior joint secretary general Fakhrul Islam Alamgir, BNP chairperson Khaleda's advisor Abdul Halim, among others, were present at the press briefing. 
